From: NeilBrown <neilb@suse.com>
Subject: nfsd: fix race between laundromat and free_stateid()
References: CVE-2024-50106 bsc#1232882
Patch-mainline: Never, lots has changed...

revoke_delegation() - called by the laundromat - can race with
free_state().  If free_state() gets the cl->lock just before
revoke_delegation() does, but still sees the new value of ->cl_state, it
can free the state, but revoke_delegation() will still put it in a list.
This can result in a use-after-free.

We fix up by updating the state after taking the lock so that if
free_stateid() does decide to free the state, it will also remove it
from the list *after* revoke_delegation() has added it to the list.

This is the same race as was fixed by 

Commit 8dd91e8d31fe ("nfsd: fix race between laundromat and free_stateid")

though it has a different form in this older kernel.

Signed-off-by: NeilBrown <neilb@suse.com>
---
 fs/nfsd/nfs4state.c |    2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

--- a/fs/nfsd/nfs4state.c
+++ b/fs/nfsd/nfs4state.c
@@ -1008,8 +1008,8 @@ static void revoke_delegation(struct nfs
 	if (clp->cl_minorversion == 0)
 		nfs4_put_stid(&dp->dl_stid);
 	else {
-		dp->dl_stid.sc_type = NFS4_REVOKED_DELEG_STID;
 		spin_lock(&clp->cl_lock);
+		dp->dl_stid.sc_type = NFS4_REVOKED_DELEG_STID;
 		list_add(&dp->dl_recall_lru, &clp->cl_revoked);
 		spin_unlock(&clp->cl_lock);
 	}
